A group of prominent Democratic lawmakers led by Sen. Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts and Reps. Pramila Jayapal of Washington and Brendan Boyle of Pennsylvania, have called on the Federal Reserve to suspend rate hikes in order to avoid risking too much damage to the US economy. The lawmakers are concerned about the Fed's monetary policy strategy and its "potential to throw millions of Americans out of work." The 10 senators and representatives raised their concerns in a letter sent to Fed Chair Jerome Powell ahead of the Fed's anticipated rate hike announcement on Wednesday.

This would be the 10th increase since last year, as the central bank has tried to tame inflation. However, some experts expect the Fed to pause hikes after Wednesday. The lawmakers called on the Fed to suspend rate hikes to "respect" its dual mandate and "avoid engineering a recession that destroys jobs and crushes small businesses." They cited the lowest year-over-year consumer price index in nine months, a resilient labor market, and a 3.5% unemployment rate, including the lowest rate for Black Americans on record, as proof that further rate hikes are unnecessary.

The benchmark federal funds rate is the highest since 2007 after nine consecutive rate increases by the Fed since last year. Seven other senators and members of the House also signed the letter addressed to Powell. The failures of Silicon Valley Bank and Signature Bank in March, combined with the "lagging impacts of the Fed's earlier rate hikes," have also left the US economy "even more vulnerable to an overreaction by the Fed," the lawmakers wrote.

They argued that successive rate hikes would "needlessly" threaten the progress made so far. They wrote, "While the Fed should remain flexible to incoming data as it assesses the economy's progress toward achieving lower inflation, the evidence to date suggests that progress can continue to be made without slamming the brakes on the economy and costing millions of Americans their jobs." The lawmakers requested a list of data points, including expected trends for wage growth and economic forecasts for the unemployment rate over the next year, in order to gauge the Fed's latest economic projections by May 15.
